      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented verification tests and change logs maintained throughout the study.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 19.2 was used under a validated installation with documented version control. Solver regression tests were executed and archived. All simulation input files were stored in a version-controlled repository, satisfying MRL 2 requirements for software quality assurance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver passes standard benchmark problems (lid-driven cavity, pipe flow) at required accuracy levels.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver was verified against the lid-driven cavity benchmark (Re=1000) and fully-developed pipe flow. Numerical errors were within 1% of analytical solutions, confirming code correctness at the level required for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) below 5% for hemolysis index QOI across three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed on the FDA pump geometry. GCI values for the normalized index of hemolysis ranged from 1.8% to 3.4% across the five operating points, remaining below the 5% threshold. The medium mesh (4.2M cells) was selected for production runs as the optimal cost-accuracy trade-off."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) are documented and replicated in the CFD model within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Experimental conditions from the FDA benchmark dataset were reproduced in the CFD model. Inlet flow rates (2.5–6.0 L/min) and impeller speeds (2000–3500 RPM) matched measurements within ±2%. Blood analog fluid properties (glycerol-water, viscosity 3.5 mPa·s) were applied consistently across all simulations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) agrees with experimental measurements within a factor of 2 across all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Simulated NIH values were compared against experimental measurements from Morrison et al. (2012). Predicted values fell within a factor of 1.6 of experimental data at all five operating points. The relative hemolysis index RH remained below 1.0 for the nominal design, satisfying the primary acceptance criterion."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QOIs used in validation (NIH, pressure rise, shear stress distribution) are directly linked to the COU decision criterion (RH < 1).",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis is the direct precursor to the relative hemolysis index used as the regulatory acceptance criterion. Pressure rise and wall shear stress distributions provide mechanistic understanding supporting QOI relevance. The mapping from validation QOIs to COU decision variables is explicit and documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments use the same pump geometry, operating range, and fluid as the COU application.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry identical to the COU device. Operating conditions spanned the full clinical flow-speed envelope. The blood analog fluid matched the viscosity of human blood within 5%. Validation domain relevance to the COU is assessed as high."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor; basic solver residual convergence documented.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, detailed iterative solver error quantification beyond residual monitoring is not required. Residuals converged to 1e-5 for all equations. This factor is not assessed beyond the minimum documentation threshold acceptable at this risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; simulation setup reviewed by a second analyst.",
      "rationale": "Formal use error analysis is not required at MRL 2. A peer review of simulation setup parameters, boundary condition assignments, and post-processing scripts was conducted by a second qualified CFD analyst. No errors were identified. This satisfies the minimum threshold for this factor at the current risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model selection (SST k-omega) justified by comparison with experimental data and literature precedent for rotating machinery hemolysis.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on its established performance for rotating machinery flows with adverse pressure gradients. Sensitivity analysis comparing SST k-omega against realizable k-epsilon showed less than 8% difference in NIH predictions. Literature precedent from FDA benchmark studies supports this model form choice for blood pump hemolysis assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties and boundary conditions are traceable to documented sources with stated uncertainties.",
      "rationale": "Fluid density (1056 kg/m³), dynamic viscosity (3.5 mPa·s), and power law hemolysis constants (C=3.62e-5, α=2.416, β=0.785) are sourced from peer-reviewed literature with documented uncertainty ranges. Inlet velocity profiles were derived from calibrated flow meter measurements. All inputs are tabulated in the simulation data package with traceability references."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; FDA benchmark dataset accepted as reference standard.",
      "rationale": "Formal test sample characterization beyond what is provided in the FDA benchmark dataset is not required at MRL 2. The FDA generic pump experimental dataset is an accepted reference standard for this class of validation activity. Sample size and statistical characterization of experimental measurements are documented in the original FDA study."
    },
